pull.body:

build: Remove unnecessary executables from gitian release

This removes the following executables from the binary gitian release:

- test_bitcoin-qt[.exe]
- bench_bitcoin[.exe]

@jonasschnelli and me discussed this on IRC a few days ago - unlike the
normal `bitcoin_tests` which is useful to see if it is safe to run
bitcoin on a certain OS/environment combination, there is no good reason
to include these. Better to leave them out to reduce the download
size.

Sizes from the 0.12 release:
```
2.4M bitcoin-0.12.0/bin/bench_bitcoin.exe
 22M bitcoin-0.12.0/bin/test_bitcoin-qt.exe
```

init: allow shutdown during 'Activating best chain...'

Two-line patch to make it possible to shut down bitcoind cleanly during
the initial ActivateBestChain.

Fixes #6459 (among other complaints).

To reproduce:

- shutdown bitcoind
- copy chainstate
- start bitcoind
- let the chain sync a bit
- shutdown bitcoind
- copy back old chainstate
- start bitcoind
- bitcoind will catch up with all blocks during Init()

(the `boost::this_thread::interruption_point` / `ShutdownRequested()`
dance is ugly, this should be refactored all over bitcoind at some point
when moving from boost::threads to c++11 threads, but it works...)

Make mining separate from the wallet

Mining uses the wallet to get a coinbase address. Pass in the
coinbase from outside instead.

Additionally, this groups the mining methods into a class giving it
a hint of object-orientation.

There are 3 ways to do 'mining'.

The RPC call 'generate'. Only usable in regtest.
This call now takes an additional argument to the public key.

The actual software miner. Started from command line or rpc as a background
thread.  Generally speaking, this is deprecated due to difficulty.
This now requires an additional commandline argument with the public key;
   -gencoinbase

The 3rd way of mining is the most used one, used by actual bitcoin miners.
Its a call to getblocktemplate.
After this commit the only way to make that work is to call -gencoinbase,
there will be a new RPC command like 'setcoinbase' which allows miners
to set a public key to mine into of their choice.

Introduce a new createaddress RPC call

this call generates an address and returns it, including the private
key.
The keys are not remembered and thus this method works without a wallet.

Add RPC call setcoinbase

Miners that want to use bitcoind to do mining, but want to avoid the
bitcoind holding their coins (security risk!) can do so.

Using createaddress to create a new address on a secure node, or
validateaddress with an existing address miners can use the RPC
interface to get hold of the pubkey needed for mining.

Using the pubkey as an argument a miner can then call setcoinbase.

Afterwards the miner can call getblocktemplate as normal.
Use precompiled headers for better gitian/windows success

Stop scaring user

Scaring user when a softfork hits 50 blocks voting when typical voting
is 1915 blocks is a bit optimistic. Stop doing this.

Track block download times per individual block

Currently, we're keeping a timeout for each requested block, starting
from when it is requested, with a correction factor for the number of
blocks in the queue.

That's unnecessarily complicated and inaccurate.

As peers process block requests in order, we can make the timeout for each
block start counting only when all previous ones have been received, and
have a correction based on the number of peers, rather than the total number
of blocks.

Reduce block timeout to 10 minutes

Now that #7804 fixed the timeout handling, reduce the block timeout from
20 minutes to 10 minutes. 20 minutes is overkill.

BIP112: Implement CHECKSEQUENCEVERIFY

- Replace NOP3 with CHECKSEQUENCEVERIFY (BIP112)
  <nSequence> CHECKSEQUENCEVERIFY -> <nSequence>
- Fails if txin.nSequence < nSequence, allowing funds of a txout to be locked for a number of blocks or a duration of time after its inclusion in a block.
- Pull most of CheckLockTime() out into VerifyLockTime(), a local function that will be reused for CheckSequence()
- Add bitwise AND operator to CScriptNum
- Enable CHECKSEQUENCEVERIFY as a standard script verify flag
- Transactions that fail CSV verification will be rejected from the mempool, making it easy to test the feature. However blocks containing "invalid" CSV-using transactions will still be accepted; this is *not* the soft-fork required to actually enable CSV for production use.

Fixes a bug in which pop_back did not call the deleted item's destructor.

Using the most general erase() implementation to implement all the others

invocation only needs to be maintained in one place.

object.

FlexTrans: Split the input-script into items.

The input-script is not really meant to bit a script. Its more a
list of crypto-graphic proofs to make the actual script on the
output work.

The idea to split the individual proofs into tokens in FlexTrans
came from SegWit and was implemented for FlexTrans in this commit.

The immediate benefit here is that we actually remove many abusive
usecases for malleability in transactions.
Because inputs are moved outside of the txid, any changes made to the input
won't cause breakages directly. But an attacker can add lots of script
which is designed to leave the stack unchanged and in that way make a
transaction substantially bigger. Which would make the transaction not be
mined should its fee be too low.

This change fixes that by limiting the inputs to only things that are
immediately pushed to the stack, in preparation of running the output
script.

I just feel I have to say something about the hackyness of this change.
Ideally we change the transaction in-memory format to reflect this change
and make the needed changes to the rest of the app.  However, there is
such an amount of technical debt that this is much more risky than this
solution.
In future we'll likely end up with a new class that represents a
transaction-v4 and we remove all these hacks from the current transaction
object and put a "don't touch" label on it.

Remove the constraint of ordering of tokens.

An often heard complaint against tokens usage was that it had to be in a
specific order.  There was really no need to actually have sections and
ordering of them so I removed that requirement.

This means that you can write a transaction where you first have the
outputs and then the inputs. If you want...

As long as the signatures are outside of the main transaction
(serialized after all the inputs and the outputs) this will work just
fine.

Implement block-size market based equilibrium.

This removes BIP109, 2MB blocksize proposal.
In its pace I insert the concept of market equilibrium based blocksizing.
Technically this means;

* We remove from the consensus rules the max-block-size.
* We introduce a command-line-argument that defines the max-block-size it
  will accept from other nodes.

Classic chose to use -blocksizeacceptlimit as a descriptive name, but for
compatibility with BU has an alias for its -excessiveblocksize.
Values are in whole megabytes, but floating point values are accepted with
an accuracy up to 100KB.  So, you can have "3.5" as blocksizeacceptlimit.
This value will be put in the coinbase-comment as "EB3.5" in this example.

In short;
Miners can continue to use the -blockmaxsize argument or bitcoin.conf
setting to limit the size of blocks they generate!  All nodes can also use
the `-blocksizeacceptlimit` option to limit the size of the blocks accepted
from (other) miners.

Introducing the new networkManager & co.

This is a properly object-oriented approach to a networking layer
for Bitcoin with several useful features;

* zero-copy sending/receiving of messages.
* lock-free operation for sending/receiving of messages.
* asynchronous operation. By default uses multithreading.
* uses zero singletons and zero global variables.
* priority-queues. (all messages are not equal).
* The network layer is messages-based, allowing the user to send
  messages to certain services on a peer, much like zmq allows.
* Optimized binary protocol, saving a lot of bandwidth.
* build in banning/punishment of misbehaving connections.
* Follows the principle of making the common easy (and fast) and the
  complex possible. For instance message-headers are autogenerated
  if not supplied, but a user can generate the whole thing if they so
  wish.

This is shipped with a proof-of-concept AdminServer. Which is meant
to wrap the RPC commands and allow them to be used with the new
network stack.

After this stabilizes the goal is set to have this be the basis
for a new p2p protocol that will likely be magnitudes faster than
the current. Not to mention easier to maintain...

Follow XDG Base Directory Spec for config files

Modifies the GetDefaultDataDir method to comply with the XDG Base Directory
Specification (https://standards.freedesktop.org/basedir-spec/basedir-spec-latest.html).
On Unix systems only:
 - If ~/.bitcoin exists, return '~/.bitcoin` (this ensures backward compatibility)
 - If the XDG_CONFIG_HOME environment variable is set, return '$XDG_CONFIG_HOME/bitcoin'
 - Otherwise, return '~/.config/bitcoin'.

Split data and config directories

Modifies the GetDefaultDataDir and GetConfigFile methods to comply with the
XDG Base Directory Specification. Only applies to unix systems.

New behavior for GetDefaultDataDir:
 - If ~/.bitcoin exists, return '~/.bitcoin` (this ensures backward compatibility)
 - If the XDG_DATA_HOME environment variable is set, return '$XDG_CONFIG_HOME/Bitcoin'
 - Otherwise return `~/.local/share/Bitcoin'

New behavior for GetConfigFile:
 - If <datadir>/bitcoin.conf exists, return '<datadir>/bitcoin.conf' (this ensures backward compatibility)
 - If the XDG_CONFIG_HOME environment variable is set, return '$XDG_CONFIG_HOME/Bitcoin/bitcoin.conf'
 - Otherwise return '~/.config/Bitcoin/bitcoin.conf'

Note that the directory name is now capitalized (Bitcoin). This is for
compatibility with the existing config file (~/.config/Bitcoin/Bitcoin-Qt.conf)
that is being written by the QSettings class of the gui.
